          <video>
            <title>Strobe video of a ball falling from rest</title>
            <shortcode></shortcode>
            <url>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xQ4znShlK5A</url>
            <width>300</width>
            <height>245</height>
          </video>
          <para>This means that if an object is moving upwards with some initial velocity in the vertical direction, the magnitude of the velocity in the vertical direction
          decreases until it stops (<latex>\vec{v}=0</latex> 
          <unit>m·s
          <sup>-1</sup></unit>) for an instant. The point at which the velocity is reduced to zero corresponds with the maximum height, <latex>h_m</latex>, that the object reaches. After this, the object
          starts to fall. It is very important to remember that the acceleration is constant but the velocity vector has changed magnitude and direction. At the maximum height where the velocity is zero the acceleration is still <latex>\vec{g}</latex>.</para>
          <note type="tip">
            <para>Projectiles that have an initial velocity upwards will have zero velocity at their greatest height, <latex>h_m</latex>. The acceleration is still <latex>\vec{g}</latex>.</para>
          </note>
