          <worked_example>
            <title>Drawing graphs of projectile motion</title>
            <question>
              <para>Stanley is standing on a balcony 
              <unit_number>
                <number>
                  <coeff>20</coeff>
                </number>
                <unit>m</unit>
              </unit_number> above the ground. Stanley tosses a rubber ball upwards with an initial velocity of 
              <unit_number>
                <number>
                  <coeff>4.9</coeff>
                </number>
                <unit>m·s
                <sup>-1</sup></unit>
              </unit_number>. The ball travels upwards to a maximum height, and then falls to the ground. Draw graphs of position vs time,
              velocity vs time and acceleration vs time. Choose upwards as the positive direction.</para>
                <pspicture>
                  <code>(-0.5,-0.5)(4.9,5.5) 
                  
                  
                  \psframe[fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=darkgray](0,0)(1,5) 
                  \psframe[fillcolor=darkgray,fillstyle=solid](1,4)(1.4,4.2) 

\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!20!white](1.45,4.2)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!35!white](1.45,5)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!50!white](1.45,3.75)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!65!white](1.45,2.5)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!80!white](1.45,1.25)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black](1.45,0)

                  
                  \psline(1,0)(2.4,0)
                  \psline[linecolor=orange]{-&gt;}(2.5,3.95)(2.5,3.55) 
                  \uput[r](2.5,3.75){$g=$ 
                  <unit_number>
                    <number>9.8</number>
                    <unit>m·s
                    <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                  </unit_number>} 
\psline[linecolor=purple]{-&gt;}(2.5,3.1)(2.5,3.5)
                  
\uput[r](2.5,3.3){$v_i=$<unit_number><number>4.9</number><unit>m·s
                    <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                                      </unit_number>}
                  
\uput[r](2.5,4.2){$v_f=$<unit_number><number>0</number><unit>m·s
                    <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                                      </unit_number>} 

%\psline[linewidth=1pt](1.4,4.2)(1.4,4.8)
                  
%\pscurve(1.4,4.8)(1.6,5)(1.8,4.8) 
%\psline[linewidth=1pt]{-&gt;}(1.8,4.8)(1.8,0)
                  
\psline[linecolor=lightgray,linestyle=dotted](1,5)(2.5,5)
</code>
                </pspicture>


            </question>
            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>Determine what is required</title>
                <para>We are required to draw graphs of:</para>
                <list list-type="enumerated">
                  <item>
                    <para>
                    <latex>\Delta \vec{x}</latex> vs <latex>t</latex></para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>
                    <latex>\vec{v}</latex> vs 
                    <latex>t</latex></para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>
                    <latex>\vec{a}</latex> vs 
                    <latex>t</latex></para>
                  </item>
                </list>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Determine how to approach the problem</title>
                <para>There are two parts to the motion of the ball:</para>
                <list list-type="enumerated">
                  <item>
                    <para>ball travelling upwards from the building</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>ball falling to the ground</para>
                  </item>
                </list>
                <para>We examine each of these parts separately. To be able to draw the graphs, we need to determine
                the time taken and displacement for each of the motions.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the height and the time taken for the first motion</title>
                <para>For the first part of the motion we have:</para>
                <list list-type="bulleted">
                  <item>
                    <para>
                      <latex>\vec{v}_{i}=
                      <unit_number>
                        <number>+4.9</number>
                        <unit>m·s
                        <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                      </unit_number></latex>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>
                      <latex>\vec{v}_{f}= 
                      <unit_number>
                        <number>0</number>
                        <unit>m·s
                        <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                      </unit_number></latex>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
                    <para>
                      <latex>\vec{g}=
                      <unit_number>
                        <number>-9.8</number>
                        <unit>m·s
                        <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                      </unit_number></latex>
                    </para>
                  </item>
                </list>


                <pspicture>
                  <code>(-0.5,-0.5)(4.9,5.5) 
                  
                  
                  \psframe[fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=darkgray](0,0)(1,5) 
                  \psframe[fillcolor=darkgray,fillstyle=solid](1,4)(1.4,4.2) 

\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!20!white](1.45,4.2)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!35!white](1.45,5)
%\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!50!white](1.45,3.75)
%\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!65!white](1.45,2.5)
%\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!80!white](1.45,1.25)
%\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black](1.45,0)

                  
                  \psline(1,0)(2.4,0)
                  \psline[linecolor=orange]{-&gt;}(2.5,3.95)(2.5,3.55) 
                  \uput[r](2.5,3.75){$\vec{g}=$ 
                  <unit_number>
                    <number>-9.8</number>
                    <unit>m·s
                    <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                  </unit_number>} 
\psline[linecolor=purple]{-&gt;}(2.5,3.1)(2.5,3.5)
                  
\uput[r](2.5,3.3){$v_i=$<unit_number><number>4.9</number><unit>m·s
                    <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                                      </unit_number>}
                  
\uput[r](2.5,4.2){$v_f=$<unit_number><number>0</number><unit>m·s<sup>-2</sup></unit></unit_number>}

%\psline[linewidth=1pt](1.4,4.2)(1.4,4.8)
                  
%\pscurve(1.4,4.8)(1.6,5)(1.8,4.8) 
%\psline[linewidth=1pt]{-&gt;}(1.8,4.8)(1.8,0)
                  
\psline[linecolor=lightgray,linestyle=dotted](1,5)(2.5,5)
</code>
                </pspicture>



                <para>Therefore we can use 
                <latex>\vec{v}_{f}^{2}=\vec{v}_{i}^{2}+2\vec{g}\Delta \vec{x}</latex> to solve for the height and 
                <latex>\vec{v}_{f}=\vec{v}_{i}+\vec{g}t</latex> to solve for the time.</para>
                <latex display='block'>
                \begin{align} 
                \vec{v}_{f}^{2}&amp; = \vec{v}_{i}^{2}+2\vec{g}\Delta \vec{x} \\
                {\left(0\right)}^{2}&amp; = {\left( <number>4.9</number>\right)}^{2}+2\times \left(<number>-9.8</number>\right)\times \Delta \vec{x} \\
                <number>19.6</number>\Delta x&amp; = {\left(<number>4.9</number>\right)}^{2} \\
                \Delta \vec{x}&amp; =  <unit_number><number>1.225</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number> 
                \end{align}
                </latex>
                <latex display='block'>
                \begin{align} \vec{v}_{f}&amp; = \vec{v}_{i}+\vec{g}t \\
 0&amp; = 
                <number>4.9</number>+\left(
                <number>-9.8</number>\right)\times t \\ 
                <number>9.8</number>t&amp; = 
                <number>4.9</number>\\
 t&amp; = 
                <unit_number><number>0.5</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> \end{align}</latex>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the height and the time taken for the second motion</title>
                <pspicture>
                  <code>(-0.5,-0.5)(4.9,5.5) 
                  
                  
                  \psframe[fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=darkgray](0,0)(1,5) 
                  \psframe[fillcolor=darkgray,fillstyle=solid](1,4)(1.4,4.2) 

\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!35!white](1.45,5)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!50!white](1.45,3.75)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!65!white](1.45,2.5)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black!80!white](1.45,1.25)
\psdots[dotsize=4pt,linecolor=black](1.45,0)

                  
                  \psline(1,0)(2.4,0)
                  \psline[linecolor=orange]{-&gt;}(2.5,3.95)(2.5,3.55) 
                  \uput[r](2.5,3.75){$g=$ 
                  <unit_number>
                    <number>9.8</number>
                    <unit>m·s
                    <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                  </unit_number>} 
\psline[linecolor=purple]{-&gt;}(2.5,3.1)(2.5,3.5)
                  
\uput[r](2.5,3.3){$v_i=$<unit_number><number>0</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>}
                  
\uput[r](2.5,4.2){$v_f=$?<unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit>} 

%\psline[linewidth=1pt](1.4,4.2)(1.4,4.8)
                  
%\pscurve(1.4,4.8)(1.6,5)(1.8,4.8) 
%\psline[linewidth=1pt]{-&gt;}(1.8,4.8)(1.8,0)
                  
\psline[linecolor=lightgray,linestyle=dotted](1,5)(2.5,5)
</code>
                </pspicture>


                <para>For the second part of the motion we have:</para>
                <list list-type="bulleted">
