            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the height of the window</title>
                <para>The initial position of the ball will tell us how high the window is. From the y-axis on the
                graph we can see that the ball is 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>4</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m</unit>
                </unit_number> from the ground.</para>
                <para>The window is therefore 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>4</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m</unit>
                </unit_number> above the ground.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the time taken to reach the maximum height</title>
                <para>The maximum height is where the position vs time graph reaches its maximum position.
                This is when t = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>0.2</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number>.</para>
                <para>It takes the ball 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>0.2</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number> to reach the maximum height.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the initial velocity (
                <latex>\vec{v}_{i}</latex>) of the ball</title>
                <para>To find the initial velocity we only look at the first part of the motion of the ball. That is
                from when the ball is released until it reaches its maximum height. We have the following for this: In
                this case, let's choose upwards as positive.</para>
                <latex display='block'>\begin{align} t&amp; = 
                <number>0.2</number> \text{s} \\
 \vec{g}&amp; = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>9.8</number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                </unit_number>\\
 \vec{v}_{f}&amp; = 0 \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1} \text{(because the ball stops)}
                \end{align}</latex>
                <para>To calculate the initial velocity of the ball (
                <latex>\vec{v}_{i}</latex>), we use:</para>
                <latex display='block'>\begin{align} \vec{v}_{f}&amp; = \vec{v}_{i}+\vec{g}t \\
 0&amp; = \vec{v}_{i}+\left(
                <number>-9.8</number>\right)\left(
                <number>0.2</number>\right) \\
 {v}_{i}&amp; = 
                <number>1.96</number> \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1} \end{align}</latex>
                <para>The initial velocity of the ball is 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>1.96</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                </unit_number>upwards.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the maximum height of the ball</title>
                <para>To find the maximum height we look at the initial motion of the ball. We have the
                following:</para>
                <latex display='block'>\begin{align} t&amp; = 
                <number>0.2</number> \text{s} \\
 \vec{g}&amp; = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>9.8</number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                </unit_number>\\
 \vec{v}_{f}&amp; = <number>0</number> \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}~\text{(because the ball stops)} \\
                \vec{v}_{i}&amp; = 
                <number>+1.96</number> \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1}\text{(calculated above)} \end{align}</latex>
                <para>To calculate the displacement from the window to the maximum height (<latex>\Delta x</latex>) we use:</para>
                <latex display='block'>\begin{align} \Delta \vec{x}&amp; = \vec{v}_{i}t+\frac{1}{2}\vec{g}{t}^{2} \\
 \Delta \vec{x}&amp; =
                \left(
                <number>1.96</number>\right)\left(
                <number>0.2</number>\right)+\frac{1}{2}\left(
                <number>-9.8</number>\right){\left(
                <number>0.2</number>\right)}^{2} \\
 \Delta \vec{x}&amp; = 
                <number>0.196</number> \text{m} \end{align}</latex>
                <para>The maximum height of the ball is 
                <latex>\left(<number>4</number>+<number>0.196</number>\right)=
                <number>4.196</number> \text{m}</latex> above the ground.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Find the final velocity (
                <latex>\vec{v}_{f}</latex>) of the ball</title>
                <para>To find the final velocity of the ball we look at the second part of the motion. For this we
                have:</para>
                <latex display='block'>\begin{align} \Delta \vec{x}&amp; = 
                <number>-4.196</number> \text{m}~\text{(because upwards is positive)} \\
 \vec{g}&amp; = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>-9.8</number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-2</sup></unit>
                </unit_number>\\
 \vec{v}_{i}&amp; = <number>0</number> \text{m}·{\text{s}}^{-1} \end{align}</latex>
                <para>We can use 
                <latex>\vec{v}^2_{f}=\vec{v}^2_{i}+2\vec{g}\Delta\vec{x}</latex> to calculate the final
                velocity of the ball.</para>
                <latex display='block'>\begin{align} 
                \vec{v}^2_{f}=\vec{v}^2_{i}+2\vec{g}\Delta\vec{x} \\
                \vec{v}^2_{f}&amp; = {\left(0\right)}^{2}+2\left(
                <number>-9.8</number>\right)\left(
                <number>-4.196</number>\right) \\
 \vec{v}^2_{f}&amp; = 
                <number>82.2416</number>\\
 \vec{v}_{f}&amp; = 
                <unit_number><number>9.0687</number><unit>m·s<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>~\text{downwards} \end{align}</latex>
                <para>The final velocity of the ball is 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>9.07</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                </unit_number>
                <emphasis effect="italics">downwards</emphasis>.</para>
              </workstep>
            </answer>
