                </unit_number></latex> the velocity of the ball is 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>0</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                </unit_number> and therefore it stops.</para>
                <para>From  <latex>t=<unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>2</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number> </latex> to  <latex>t=<unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>4</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number></latex> the following happens:</para>
                <para>The ball moves from a velocity of 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>0</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                </unit_number> to 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>19.6</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>m·s
                  <sup>-1</sup></unit>
                </unit_number> in the opposite direction to the original motion.</para>
                <para>If we assume that the ball is hit straight up in the air (and we take upwards as positive), it
                reaches its maximum height at  <latex>t=
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>2</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number></latex>, stops, and falls back to the Earth to reach the ground 
                at  <latex>t=
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>4</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number> </latex>.</para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Draw the displacement-time graph</title>
                <para>To draw this graph, we need to determine the displacements at  <latex>t = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>2</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number> </latex> and  <latex>t = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>4</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number> </latex>.</para>
                <para>At  <latex>t = 
                <unit_number>
                  <number>
                    <coeff>2</coeff>
                  </number>
                  <unit>s</unit>
                </unit_number> </latex>:</para>
                <para>The displacement is equal to the area under the graph:</para>
                <para>Area under graph = Area of triangle</para>
                <para>
                  <latex>\text{Area}=\frac{1}{2}bh</latex>
                </para>
                <para>
                  <latex>\text{Area}=\frac{1}{2}\times 2\times 
                  <number>19.6</number></latex>
